# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sheaf-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] In category theory, a branch of mathematics, a **Grothendieck topology** is a structure on a category ${\mathcal {C}}$ that makes the objects of ${\mathcal {C}}$ act like the open sets of a topological space.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] A category together with a choice of Grothendieck topology is called a **site**.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Grothendieck topologies axiomatize the notion of an open cover.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Using the notion of covering provided by a Grothendieck topology, it becomes possible to define sheaves on a category and their cohomology.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] This was first done in algebraic geometry and algebraic number theory by Alexander Grothendieck to define the étale cohomology of a scheme.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] It has been used to define other cohomology theories since then, such as ℓ-adic cohomology, flat cohomology, and crystalline cohomology.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] While Grothendieck topologies are most often used to define cohomology theories, they have found other applications as well, such as to John Tate's theory of rigid analytic geometry.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] There is a natural way to associate a site to an ordinary topological space, and Grothendieck's theory is loosely regarded as a generalization of classical topology.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Under meager point-set hypotheses, namely sobriety, this is completely accurate—it is possible to recover a sober space from its associated site.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] However simple examples such as the indiscrete topological space show that not all topological spaces can be expressed using Grothendieck topologies.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Conversely, there are Grothendieck topologies that do not come from topological spaces.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] The term "Grothendieck topology" has changed in meaning.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] In Artin (1962) it meant what is now called a Grothendieck pretopology, and some authors still use this old meaning.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Giraud (1964) modified the definition to use sieves rather than covers.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Much of the time this does not make much difference, as each Grothendieck pretopology determines a unique Grothendieck topology, though quite different pretopologies can give the same topology.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] André Weil's famous Weil conjectures proposed that certain properties of equations with integral coefficients should be understood as geometric properties of the algebraic variety that they define.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] His conjectures postulated that there should be a cohomology theory of algebraic varieties that gives number-theoretic information about their defining equations.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] This cohomology theory was known as the "Weil cohomology", but using the tools he had available, Weil was unable to construct it.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] In the early 1960s, Alexander Grothendieck introduced étale maps into algebraic geometry as algebraic analogues of local analytic isomorphisms in analytic geometry.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] He used étale coverings to define an algebraic analogue of the fundamental group of a topological space.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Soon Jean-Pierre Serre noticed that some properties of étale coverings mimicked those of open immersions, and that consequently it was possible to make constructions that imitated the cohomology functor $H^{1}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Grothendieck saw that it would be possible to use Serre's idea to define a cohomology theory that he suspected would be the Weil cohomology.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] To define this cohomology theory, Grothendieck needed to replace the usual, topological notion of an open covering with one that would use étale coverings instead.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Grothendieck also saw how to phrase the definition of covering abstractly; this is where the definition of a Grothendieck topology comes from.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] The classical definition of a sheaf begins with a topological space X .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] A sheaf associates information to the open sets of X .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] This information can be phrased abstractly by letting $O(X)$ be the category whose objects are the open subsets U of X and whose morphisms are the inclusion maps $V\to U$ of open sets U and V of X .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] We will call such maps *open immersions*, just as in the context of schemes.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Then a presheaf on X is a contravariant functor from $O(X)$ to the category of sets, and a sheaf is a presheaf that satisfies the gluing axiom (here including the separation axiom).
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] The gluing axiom is phrased in terms of pointwise covering, i.e., $\{U_{i}\}$ covers U if and only if $\bigcup _{i}U_{i}=U$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] In this definition, $U_{i}$ is an open subset of X .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Grothendieck topologies replace each $U_{i}$ with an entire family of open subsets; in this example, $U_{i}$ is replaced by the family of all open immersions $V_{ij}\to U_{i}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Pointwise covering is replaced by the notion of a *covering family*; in the above example, the set of all $\{V_{ij}\to U_{i}\}_{j}$ as i varies is a covering family of U .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Sieves and covering families can be axiomatized, and once this is done open sets and pointwise covering can be replaced by other notions that describe other properties of the space X .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] In a Grothendieck topology, the notion of a collection of open subsets of U stable under inclusion is replaced by the notion of a sieve.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] If c is any given object in ${\mathcal {C}}$ , a **sieve** on c is a subfunctor of the functor $\operatorname {Hom} (-,c)$ ; (this is the Yoneda embedding applied to c ).
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] In the case of $O(X)$ , a sieve S on an open set U selects a collection of open subsets of U that is stable under inclusion.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] More precisely, consider that for any open subset V of U , $S(V)$ will be a subset of $\operatorname {Hom} (V,U)$ , which has only one element, the open immersion $V\to U$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Then V will be considered "selected" by S if and only if $S(V)$ is nonempty.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] If W is a subset of V , then there is a morphism $S(V)\to S(W)$ given by composition with the inclusion $W\to V$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] If $S(V)$ is non-empty, it follows that $S(W)$ is also non-empty.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] If S is a sieve on X , and $f:Y\to X$ is a morphism, then left composition by f gives a sieve on Y called the **pullback of** S **along** f , denoted by $f^{*}S$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] It is defined as the fibered product $S\times _{\operatorname {Hom} (-,X)}\operatorname {Hom} (-,Y)$ together with its natural embedding in $\operatorname {Hom} (-,Y)$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] More concretely, for each object Z of ${\mathcal {C}}$ , $f^{*}S(Z)=\{g:Z\to Y\mid fg\in S(Z)\},$ and $f^{*}S$ inherits its action on morphisms by being a subfunctor of $\operatorname {Hom} (-,Y)$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] In the classical example, the pullback of a collection $\{V_{i}\}$ of subsets of U along an inclusion $W\to U$ is the collection $\{V_{i}\cap W\}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] A **Grothendieck topology** J on a category ${\mathcal {C}}$ is a collection, *for each object c of ${\mathcal {C}}$*, of distinguished sieves on c , denoted by $J(c)$ and called **covering sieves** of c .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] This selection will be subject to certain axioms, stated below.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Continuing the previous example, a sieve S on an open set U in $O(X)$ will be a covering sieve if and only if the union of all the open sets V for which $S(V)$ is nonempty equals U ; in other words, if and only if S gives us a collection of open sets that cover U in the classical sense.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] The base change axiom corresponds to the idea that if $\{U_{i}:i\in I\}$ covers U , then $\{U_{i}\cap V:i\in I\}$ covers $U\cap V$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] The local character axiom corresponds to the idea that if $\{U_{i}:i\in I\}$ covers U and $\{V_{j}\cap U_{i}:j\in J\}$ covers $U_{i}$ for each i , then the collection $\{V_{j}:j\in J\}$ covers U .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] The identity axiom corresponds to the idea that, at least when U is an open set, the set of open subsets of U covers U .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] In fact, it is possible to put these axioms in another form where their geometric character is more apparent, assuming that the underlying category ${\mathcal {C}}$ contains certain fibered products.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] In this case, instead of specifying sieves, we can specify that certain collections of maps with a common codomain should cover their codomain.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] These collections are called **covering families**.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] If the collection of all covering families satisfies certain axioms, then we say that they form a **Grothendieck pretopology**.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] For any pretopology, the collection of all sieves that contain a covering family from the pretopology is always a Grothendieck topology.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] For categories with fibered products, there is a converse.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Given a collection of arrows $\{X_{\alpha }\to X\}$ , we construct a sieve S by letting $S(Y)$ be the set of all morphisms $Y\to X$ that factor through some arrow $X_{\alpha }\to X$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] This is called the sieve **generated by** $\{X_{\alpha }\to X\}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Say that $\{X_{\alpha }\to X\}$ is a covering family if and only if the sieve that it generates is a covering sieve for the given topology.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] It is easy to check that this defines a pretopology.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] (PT 3) implies (PT 3'), but not conversely.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] However, suppose that we have a collection of covering families that satisfies (PT 0) through (PT 2) and (PT 3'), but not (PT 3).
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] The topology generated by the original collection of covering families is then the same as the topology generated by the pretopology, because the sieve generated by an isomorphism $Y\to X$ is $\operatorname {Hom} (-,X)$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Consequently, if we restrict our attention to topologies, (PT 3) and (PT 3') are equivalent.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Let ${\mathcal {C}}$ be a category and let J be a Grothendieck topology on ${\mathcal {C}}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] A **presheaf** on a category is a contravariant functor from ${\mathcal {C}}$ to the category of all sets.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Note that for this definition ${\mathcal {C}}$ is not required to have a topology.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] A sheaf on a site, however, should allow gluing, just like sheaves in classical topology.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Halfway in between a presheaf and a sheaf is the notion of a **separated presheaf**, where the natural map above is required to be only an injection, not a bijection, for all sieves S .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] A **morphism** of presheaves or of sheaves is a natural transformation of functors.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] The category of all sheaves on ${\mathcal {C}}$ is the **topos** defined by the site ( ${\mathcal {C}},J$ ).
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Using the Yoneda lemma, it is possible to show that a presheaf on the category $O(X)$ is a sheaf on the topology defined above if and only if it is a sheaf in the classical sense.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] For a separated presheaf, the first arrow need only be injective.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Similarly, one can define presheaves and sheaves of abelian groups, rings, modules, and so on.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] One can require either that a presheaf F is a contravariant functor to the category of abelian groups (or rings, or modules, etc.), or that F be an abelian group (ring, module, etc.) object in the category of all contravariant functors from ${\mathcal {C}}$ to the category of sets.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] To define the **discrete topology**, we declare all sieves to be covering sieves.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] If ${\mathcal {C}}$ has all fibered products, this is equivalent to declaring all families to be covering families.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] To define the **indiscrete topology**, also known as the **coarse** or **chaotic** topology, we declare only the sieves of the form $\operatorname {Hom} (-,X)$ to be covering sieves.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] The indiscrete topology is generated by the pretopology that has only isomorphisms for covering families.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] A sheaf on the indiscrete site is the same thing as a presheaf.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] The Yoneda embedding gives a functor $\operatorname {Hom} (-,X)$ for each object X of ${\mathcal {C}}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] The **canonical topology** is the biggest (finest) topology such that every representable presheaf, i.e. presheaf of the form $\operatorname {Hom} (-,X)$ , is a sheaf.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] A covering sieve or covering family for this site is said to be *strictly universally epimorphic* because it consists of the legs of a colimit cone (under the full diagram on the domains of its constituent morphisms) and these colimits are stable under pullbacks along morphisms in ${\mathcal {C}}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] A topology that is less fine than the canonical topology, that is, for which every covering sieve is strictly universally epimorphic, is called **subcanonical**.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Subcanonical sites are exactly the sites for which every presheaf of the form $\operatorname {Hom} (-,X)$ is a sheaf.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Most sites encountered in practice are subcanonical.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] We repeat the example that we began with above.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] We defined $O(X)$ to be the category whose objects are the open sets of X and whose morphisms are inclusions of open sets.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Note that for an open set U and a sieve S on U , the set $S(V)$ contains either zero or one element for every open set V .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] This notion of cover matches the usual notion in point-set topology.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] This topology can also naturally be expressed as a pretopology.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] We say that a family of inclusions $\{V_{\alpha }\subseteq U\}$ is a covering family if and only if the union $\cup V_{\alpha }=U$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] This site is called the **small site associated to a topological space** X .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Let ${\mathcal {S}}pc$ be the category of all topological spaces.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Given any family of functions $\{u_{\alpha }:V_{\alpha }\to X\}$ , we say that it is a **surjective family** or that the morphisms $u_{\alpha }$ are **jointly surjective** if $\cup u_{\alpha }(V_{\alpha })=X$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] We define a pretopology on ${\mathcal {S}}pc$ by taking the covering families to be surjective families all of whose members are open immersions.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Let S be a sieve on ${\mathcal {S}}pc$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Consider the comma category ${\mathcal {S}}pc/X$ of topological spaces with a fixed continuous map to X .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] The topology on ${\mathcal {S}}pc$ induces a topology on ${\mathcal {S}}pc/X$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] The covering sieves and covering families are almost exactly the same; the only difference is that now all the maps involved commute with the fixed maps to X .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] This is the **big site associated to a topological space** X .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Notice that ${\mathcal {S}}pc$ is the big site associated to the one point space.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] This site was first considered by Jean Giraud.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] M has a category of open sets $O(M)$ because it is a topological space, and it gets a topology as in the above example.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] For two open sets U and V of M , the fiber product $U\times _{M}V$ is the open set $U\cap V$ , which is still in $O(M)$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] This means that the topology on $O(M)$ is defined by a pretopology, the same pretopology as before.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Let ${\mathcal {M}}fd$ be the category of all manifolds and continuous maps.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] (Or smooth manifolds and smooth maps, or real analytic manifolds and analytic maps, etc.) ${\mathcal {M}}fd$ is a subcategory of ${\mathcal {S}}pc$ , and open immersions are continuous (or smooth, or analytic, etc.), so ${\mathcal {M}}fd$ inherits a topology from ${\mathcal {S}}pc$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] This lets us construct the big site of the manifold M as the site ${\mathcal {M}}fd/M$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] We can also define this topology using the same pretopology we used above.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Notice that to satisfy (PT 0), we need to check that for any continuous map of manifolds $X\to Y$ and any open subset U of Y , the fibered product $U\times _{Y}X$ is in ${\mathcal {M}}fd/M$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] This is just the statement that the preimage of an open set is open.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Notice, however, that not all fibered products exist in ${\mathcal {M}}fd$ because the preimage of a smooth map at a critical value need not be a manifold.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] The category of schemes, denoted ${\mathcal {S}}ch$ , has a tremendous number of useful topologies.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] A complete understanding of some questions may require examining a scheme using several different topologies.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] All of these topologies have associated small and big sites.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] The big site is formed by taking the entire category of schemes and their morphisms, together with the covering sieves specified by the topology.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] The small site over a given scheme is formed by only taking the objects and morphisms that are part of a cover of the given scheme.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] The most elementary of these is the Zariski topology.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] X has an underlying topological space, and this topological space determines a Grothendieck topology.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] The Zariski topology on ${\mathcal {S}}ch$ is generated by the pretopology whose covering families are jointly surjective families of scheme-theoretic open immersions.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Despite their outward similarities, the topology on $Zar$ is *not* the restriction of the topology on ${\mathcal {S}}pc$ !
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] This is because there are morphisms of schemes that are topologically open immersions but that are not scheme-theoretic open immersions.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] For example, let A be a non-reduced ring and let N be its ideal of nilpotents.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] The quotient map $A\to A/N$ induces a map $\operatorname {Spec} A/N\to \operatorname {Spec} A$ , which is the identity on underlying topological spaces.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] To be a scheme-theoretic open immersion it must also induce an isomorphism on structure sheaves, which this map does not do.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] In fact, this map is a closed immersion.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] The étale topology is finer than the Zariski topology.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] It was the first Grothendieck topology to be closely studied.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Its covering families are jointly surjective families of étale morphisms.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] It is finer than the Nisnevich topology, but neither finer nor coarser than the *cdh* and l′ topologies.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] There are two flat topologies, the *fppf* topology and the *fpqc* topology.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] *fppf* stands for **fidèlement plate de présentation finie**, and in this topology, a morphism of affine schemes is a covering morphism if it is faithfully flat, of finite presentation, and is quasi-finite.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] *fpqc* stands for **fidèlement plate et quasi-compacte**, and in this topology, a morphism of affine schemes is a covering morphism if it is faithfully flat.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] In both categories, a covering family is defined to be a family that is a cover on Zariski open subsets.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] In the fpqc topology, any faithfully flat and quasi-compact morphism is a cover.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] These topologies are closely related to descent.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] The *fpqc* topology is finer than all the topologies mentioned above, and it is very close to the canonical topology.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Grothendieck introduced crystalline cohomology to study the p -torsion part of the cohomology of characteristic p varieties.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] In the *crystalline topology*, which is the basis of this theory, the underlying category has objects given by infinitesimal thickenings together with divided power structures.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Crystalline sites are examples of sites with no final object.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] There are two natural types of functors between sites.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] They are given by functors that are compatible with the topology in a certain sense.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] If ( ${\mathcal {C}},J$ ) and ( ${\mathcal {D}},K$ ) are sites and $u:{\mathcal {C}}\to {\mathcal {D}}$ is a functor, then u is **continuous** if for every sheaf F on ${\mathcal {D}}$ with respect to the topology K , the presheaf $Fu$ is a sheaf with respect to the topology J .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Continuous functors induce functors between the corresponding topoi by sending a sheaf F to $Fu$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] These functors are called **pushforwards**.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] If ${\tilde {\mathcal {C}}}$ and ${\tilde {\mathcal {D}}}$ denote the topoi associated to ${\mathcal {C}}$ and ${\mathcal {D}}$ , then the pushforward functor is $u_{s}:{\tilde {\mathcal {D}}}\to {\tilde {\mathcal {C}}}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] $u_{s}$ admits a left adjoint $u^{s}$ called the **pullback**. $u^{s}$ need not preserve limits, even finite limits.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] In the same way, u sends a sieve on an object X of ${\mathcal {C}}$ to a sieve on the object $uX$ of ${\mathcal {D}}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] A continuous functor sends covering sieves to covering sieves.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] If J is the topology defined by a pretopology, and if u commutes with fibered products, then u is continuous if and only if it sends covering sieves to covering sieves and if and only if it sends covering families to covering families.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] In general, it is *not* sufficient for u to send covering sieves to covering sieves (see SGA IV 3, *Exemple* 1.9.3).
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] If X is an object of ${\mathcal {C}}$ and R is a sieve on $vX$ , then R can be pulled back to a sieve S as follows: A morphism $f:Z\to X$ is in S if and only if $v(f):vZ\to vX$ is in R .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] This defines a sieve. v is **cocontinuous** if and only if for every object X of ${\mathcal {C}}$ and every covering sieve R of $vX$ , the pullback S of R is a covering sieve on X .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Composition with v sends a presheaf F on ${\mathcal {D}}$ to a presheaf $Fv$ on ${\mathcal {C}}$ , but if v is cocontinuous, this need not send sheaves to sheaves.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] However, this functor on presheaf categories, usually denoted ${\hat {v}}^{*}$ , admits a right adjoint ${\hat {v}}_{*}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Then v is cocontinuous if and only if ${\hat {v}}_{*}$ sends sheaves to sheaves, that is, if and only if it restricts to a functor $v_{*}:{\tilde {\mathcal {C}}}\to {\tilde {\mathcal {D}}}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] In this case, the composite of ${\hat {v}}^{*}$ with the associated sheaf functor is a left adjoint of $v_{*}$ denoted $v^{*}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Furthermore, $v^{*}$ preserves finite limits, so the adjoint functors $v_{*}$ and $v^{*}$ determine a geometric morphism of topoi ${\tilde {\mathcal {C}}}\to {\tilde {\mathcal {D}}}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] A continuous functor $u:{\mathcal {C}}\to {\mathcal {D}}$ is a **morphism of sites** ${\mathcal {D}}\to {\mathcal {C}}$ (*not* ${\mathcal {C}}\to {\mathcal {D}}$ ) if $u^{s}$ preserves finite limits.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] In this case, $u^{s}$ and $u_{s}$ determine a geometric morphism of topoi ${\tilde {\mathcal {C}}}\to {\tilde {\mathcal {D}}}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] The reasoning behind the convention that a continuous functor ${\mathcal {C}}\to {\mathcal {D}}$ is said to determine a morphism of sites in the opposite direction is that this agrees with the intuition coming from the case of topological spaces.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] A continuous map of topological spaces $X\to Y$ determines a continuous functor $O(Y)\to O(X)$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Since the original map on topological spaces is said to send X to Y , the morphism of sites is said to as well.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] A particular case of this happens when a continuous functor admits a left adjoint.
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Suppose that $u:{\mathcal {C}}\to {\mathcal {D}}$ and $v:{\mathcal {D}}\to {\mathcal {C}}$ are functors with u right adjoint to v .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] Then u is continuous if and only if v is cocontinuous, and when this happens, $u^{s}$ is naturally isomorphic to $v^{*}$ and $u_{s}$ is naturally isomorphic to $v_{*}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/grothendieck-topology] In particular, u is a morphism of sites.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] In mathematics, a **ringed space** is a family of (commutative) rings parametrized by open subsets of a topological space together with ring homomorphisms that play roles of restrictions.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] Precisely, it is a topological space equipped with a **sheaf of rings** called a **structure sheaf**.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] It is an abstraction of the concept of the rings of continuous (scalar-valued) functions on open subsets.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] Among ringed spaces, especially important and prominent is a **locally ringed space**: a ringed space in which the analogy between the stalk at a point and the ring of germs of functions at a point is valid.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] Ringed spaces appear in analysis as well as complex algebraic geometry and the scheme theory of algebraic geometry.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] A **ringed space** $(X,{\mathcal {O}}_{X})$ is a topological space *X* together with a sheaf of rings ${\mathcal {O}}_{X}$ on X .
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] The sheaf ${\mathcal {O}}_{X}$ is called the **structure sheaf** of X .
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] A **locally ringed space** is a ringed space $(X,{\mathcal {O}}_{X})$ such that all stalks of ${\mathcal {O}}_{X}$ are local rings (i.e. they have unique maximal ideals).
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] Note that it is *not* required that ${\mathcal {O}}_{X}(U)$ be a local ring for every open set U *;* in fact, this is almost never the case.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] An arbitrary topological space *X* can be considered a locally ringed space by taking *${\mathcal {O}}_{X}$* to be the sheaf of real-valued (or complex-valued) continuous functions on open subsets of *X*.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] The stalk at a point x can be thought of as the set of all germs of continuous functions at *x*; this is a local ring with the unique maximal ideal consisting of those germs whose value at *x* is 0 .
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] If *X* is a manifold with some extra structure, we can also take the sheaf of differentiable, or holomorphic functions.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] Both of these give rise to locally ringed spaces.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] If *X* is an algebraic variety carrying the Zariski topology, we can define a locally ringed space by taking ${\mathcal {O}}_{X}(U)$ to be the ring of rational mappings defined on the Zariski-open set *U* that do not blow up (become infinite) within U .
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] The important generalization of this example is that of the spectrum of any commutative ring; these spectra are also locally ringed spaces.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] Schemes are locally ringed spaces obtained by "gluing together" spectra of commutative rings.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] A morphism from $(X,{\mathcal {O}}_{X})$ to $(Y,{\mathcal {O}}_{Y})$ is a pair $(f,\varphi )$ , where $f:X\to Y$ is a continuous map between the underlying topological spaces, and ${\displaystyle \varphi$ is a morphism from the structure sheaf of Y to the direct image of the structure sheaf of *X*.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] Two morphisms can be composed to form a new morphism, and we obtain the category of ringed spaces and the category of locally ringed spaces.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] Isomorphisms in these categories are defined as usual.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] Locally ringed spaces have just enough structure to allow the meaningful definition of tangent spaces.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] Let *X* be a locally ringed space with structure sheaf *${\mathcal {O}}_{X}$*; we want to define the tangent space $T_{x}(X)$ at the point *$x\in X$*.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] Take the local ring (stalk) $R_{x}$ at the point x , with maximal ideal ${\mathfrak {m}}_{x}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] The tangent space $T_{x}(X)$ is defined as the dual of this vector space.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] The idea is the following: a tangent vector at *x* should tell you how to "differentiate" "functions" at *x*, i.e. the elements of *$R_{x}$*.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] Now it is enough to know how to differentiate functions whose value at *x* is zero, since all other functions differ from these only by a constant, and we know how to differentiate constants.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] So we only need to consider *${\mathfrak {m}}_{x}$*.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] Furthermore, if two functions are given with value zero at *x*, then their product has derivative 0 at *x*, by the product rule.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] So we only need to know how to assign "numbers" to the elements of ${\mathfrak {m}}_{x}/{\mathfrak {m}}_{x}^{2}$ , and this is what the dual space does.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] Given a locally ringed space $(X,{\mathcal {O}}_{X})$ , certain sheaves of modules on *X* occur in the applications, the *${\mathcal {O}}_{X}$*-modules.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] To define them, consider a sheaf ${\mathcal {F}}$ of abelian groups on *X*.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] If ${\mathcal {F}}(U)$ is a module over the ring *${\mathcal {O}}_{X}(U)$* for every open set *U* in *X*, and the restriction maps are compatible with the module structure, then we call ${\mathcal {F}}$ an *${\mathcal {O}}_{X}$*-module.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] In this case, the stalk of *${\mathcal {F}}$* at *x* will be a module over the local ring (stalk) *$R_{x}$*, for every *$x\in X$*.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] A morphism between two such *${\mathcal {O}}_{X}$*-modules is a morphism of sheaves that is compatible with the given module structures.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] The category of *${\mathcal {O}}_{X}$*-modules over a fixed locally ringed space $(X,{\mathcal {O}}_{X})$ is an abelian category.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] An important subcategory of the category of *${\mathcal {O}}_{X}$*-modules is the category of *quasi-coherent sheaves* on *X*.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] A sheaf of *${\mathcal {O}}_{X}$*-modules is called quasi-coherent if it is, locally, isomorphic to the cokernel of a map between free *${\mathcal {O}}_{X}$*-modules.
[src:sheaf-theory/locally-ringed-space] A *coherent* sheaf *F* is a quasi-coherent sheaf that is, locally, of finite type and for every open subset *U* of *X* the kernel of any morphism from a free *${\mathcal {O}}_{U}$*-module of finite rank to *${\mathcal {F}}_{U}$* is also of finite type.
[src:sheaf-theory/presheaf-category-theory] In category theory, a branch of mathematics, a **presheaf** on a category C is a functor $F\colon C^{\mathrm {op} }\to \mathbf {Set}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/presheaf-category-theory] If C is the poset of open sets in a topological space, interpreted as a category, then one recovers the usual notion of presheaf on a topological space.
[src:sheaf-theory/presheaf-category-theory] A morphism of presheaves is defined to be a natural transformation of functors.
[src:sheaf-theory/presheaf-category-theory] This makes the collection of all presheaves on C into a category, and is an example of a functor category.
[src:sheaf-theory/presheaf-category-theory] It is often written as ${\widehat {C}}=\mathbf {Set} ^{C^{\mathrm {op} }}$ and it is called the **category of presheaves** on C .
[src:sheaf-theory/presheaf-category-theory] A functor into ${\widehat {C}}$ is sometimes called a profunctor.
[src:sheaf-theory/presheaf-category-theory] A presheaf that is naturally isomorphic to the contravariant hom-functor Hom(–, *A*) for some object *A* of **C** is called a representable presheaf.
[src:sheaf-theory/presheaf-category-theory] Some authors refer to a functor $F\colon C^{\mathrm {op} }\to \mathbf {V}$ as a **$\mathbf {V}$ -valued presheaf**.
[src:sheaf-theory/presheaf-category-theory] where *y* is the Yoneda embedding and ${\widetilde {\eta }}:{\widehat {C}}\to D$ is a, unique up to isomorphism, colimit-preserving functor called the **Yoneda extension** of $\eta$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/presheaf-category-theory] The proposition yields several corollaries.
[src:sheaf-theory/presheaf-category-theory] For example, the proposition implies that the construction $C\mapsto {\widehat {C}}$ is functorial: i.e., each functor $C\to D$ determines the functor ${\widehat {C}}\to {\widehat {D}}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/presheaf-category-theory] A **presheaf of spaces** on an ∞-category *C* is a contravariant functor from *C* to the ∞-category of spaces (for example, the nerve of the category of CW-complexes.) It is an ∞-category version of a presheaf of sets, as a "set" is replaced by a "space".
[src:sheaf-theory/presheaf-category-theory] A **copresheaf** of a category *C* is a presheaf of *Cop*.
[src:sheaf-theory/presheaf-category-theory] In other words, it is a covariant functor from *C* to *Set*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] In mathematics, **sheaf cohomology** is the application of homological algebra to analyze the global sections of a sheaf on a topological space.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Broadly speaking, sheaf cohomology describes the obstructions (holes) to solving a geometric problem globally when it can be solved locally.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] The central work for the study of sheaf cohomology is Grothendieck's 1957 Tôhoku paper.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Sheaves, sheaf cohomology, and spectral sequences were introduced by Jean Leray at the prisoner-of-war camp Oflag XVII-A in Austria.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] From 1940 to 1945, Leray and other prisoners organized a "université en captivité" in the camp.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Leray's definitions were simplified and clarified in the 1950s.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] It became clear that sheaf cohomology was not only a new approach to cohomology in algebraic topology, but also a powerful method in complex analytic geometry and algebraic geometry.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] These subjects often involve constructing global functions with specified local properties, and sheaf cohomology is ideally suited to such problems.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Many earlier results such as the Riemann–Roch theorem and the Hodge theorem have been generalized or understood better using sheaf cohomology.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] The category of sheaves of abelian groups on a topological space *X* is an abelian category, and so it makes sense to ask when a morphism *f*: *B* → *C* of sheaves is injective (a monomorphism) or surjective (an epimorphism).
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] One answer is that *f* is injective (respectively surjective) if and only if the associated homomorphism on stalks *B**x* → *C**x* is injective (respectively surjective) for every point *x* in *X*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] It follows that *f* is injective if and only if the homomorphism *B*(*U*) → *C*(*U*) of sections over *U* is injective for every open set *U* in *X*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] As a result, the question arises: given a surjection *B* → *C* of sheaves and a section *s* of *C* over *X*, when is *s* the image of a section of *B* over *X*?
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] This is a model for all kinds of local-vs.-global questions in geometry.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Sheaf cohomology gives a satisfactory general answer.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] where *H*0(*X*,*A*) is the group *A*(*X*) of global sections of *A* on *X*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] For example, if the group *H*1(*X*,*A*) is zero, then this exact sequence implies that every global section of *C* lifts to a global section of *B*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] More broadly, the exact sequence makes knowledge of higher cohomology groups a fundamental tool in aiming to understand sections of sheaves.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Grothendieck's definition of sheaf cohomology, now standard, uses the language of homological algebra.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] The essential point is to fix a topological space *X* and think of cohomology as a functor from sheaves of abelian groups on *X* to abelian groups.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] In more detail, start with the functor *E* ↦ *E*(*X*) from sheaves of abelian groups on *X* to abelian groups.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] This is left exact, but in general not right exact.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Then the groups *H**i*(*X*,*E*) for integers *i* are defined as the right derived functors of the functor *E* ↦ *E*(*X*).
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] This makes it automatic that *H**i*(*X*,*E*) is zero for *i* < 0, and that *H*0(*X*,*E*) is the group *E*(*X*) of global sections.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] The long exact sequence above is also straightforward from this definition.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] The definition of derived functors uses that the category of sheaves of abelian groups on any topological space *X* has enough injectives; that is, for every sheaf *E* there is an injective sheaf *I* with an injection *E* → *I*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Standard arguments in homological algebra imply that these cohomology groups are independent of the choice of injective resolution of *E*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] The definition is rarely used directly to compute sheaf cohomology.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] It is nonetheless powerful, because it works in great generality (any sheaf of abelian groups on any topological space), and it easily implies the formal properties of sheaf cohomology, such as the long exact sequence above.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] For specific classes of spaces or sheaves, there are many tools for computing sheaf cohomology, some discussed below.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] for every integer *j*, where *f**(*E*) denotes the inverse image sheaf or **pullback sheaf**.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] If *f* is the inclusion of a subspace *X* of *Y*, *f**(*E*) is the **restriction** of *E* to *X*, often just called *E* again, and the pullback of a section *s* from *Y* to *X* is called the restriction *s*|*X*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Pullback homomorphisms are used in the Mayer–Vietoris sequence, an important computational result.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Namely, let *X* be a topological space which is a union of two open subsets *U* and *V*, and let *E* be a sheaf on *X*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] For a topological space X and an abelian group A , the constant sheaf $A_{X}$ means the sheaf of locally constant functions with values in A .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] The sheaf cohomology groups $H^{j}(X,A_{X})$ with constant coefficients are often written simply as $H^{j}(X,A)$ , unless this could cause confusion with another version of cohomology such as singular cohomology.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] For a continuous map *f*: *X* → *Y* and an abelian group *A*, the pullback sheaf *f**(*A**Y*) is isomorphic to *A**X*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] As a result, the pullback homomorphism makes sheaf cohomology with constant coefficients into a contravariant functor from topological spaces to abelian groups.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] It follows that two homotopy equivalent spaces have isomorphic sheaf cohomology with constant coefficients.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Let *X* be a paracompact Hausdorff space which is locally contractible, even in the weak sense that every open neighborhood *U* of a point *x* contains an open neighborhood *V* of *x* such that the inclusion *V* → *U* is homotopic to a constant map.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Then the singular cohomology groups of *X* with coefficients in an abelian group *A* are isomorphic to sheaf cohomology with constant coefficients, *H**(*X*,*A**X*).
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] For example, this holds for *X* a topological manifold or a CW complex.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] As a result, many of the basic calculations of sheaf cohomology with constant coefficients are the same as calculations of singular cohomology.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] See the article on cohomology for the cohomology of spheres, projective spaces, tori, and surfaces.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] For arbitrary topological spaces, singular cohomology and sheaf cohomology (with constant coefficients) can be different.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] The singular cohomology *H*0(*X*,**Z**) is the group of all functions from the set of path components of *X* to the integers **Z**, whereas sheaf cohomology *H*0(*X*,**Z***X*) is the group of locally constant functions from *X* to **Z**.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] These are different, for example, when *X* is the Cantor set.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] For a paracompact Hausdorff space *X* and any sheaf *E* of abelian groups on *X*, the cohomology groups *H**j*(*X*,*E*) are zero for *j* greater than the covering dimension of *X*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] A sheaf *E* of abelian groups on a topological space *X* is called **acyclic** if *H**j*(*X*,*E*) = 0 for all *j* > 0.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] By the long exact sequence of sheaf cohomology, the cohomology of any sheaf can be computed from any acyclic resolution of *E* (rather than an injective resolution).
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Injective sheaves are acyclic, but for computations it is useful to have other examples of acyclic sheaves.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] A sheaf *E* on *X* is called **flabby** (French: *flasque*) if every section of *E* on an open subset of *X* extends to a section of *E* on all of *X*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Godement defined sheaf cohomology via a canonical flabby resolution of any sheaf; since flabby sheaves are acyclic, Godement's definition agrees with the definition of sheaf cohomology above.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] A sheaf *E* on a paracompact Hausdorff space *X* is called **soft** if every section of the restriction of *E* to a closed subset of *X* extends to a section of *E* on all of *X*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Some examples of soft sheaves are the sheaf of real-valued continuous functions on any paracompact Hausdorff space, or the sheaf of smooth (*C*∞) functions on any smooth manifold.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] More generally, any sheaf of modules over a soft sheaf of commutative rings is soft; for example, the sheaf of smooth sections of a vector bundle over a smooth manifold is soft.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] For example, these results form part of the proof of de Rham's theorem.
