[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] By the results above, the sheaves Ω*X**j* are soft and therefore acyclic.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] The other part of de Rham's theorem is to identify sheaf cohomology and singular cohomology of *X* with real coefficients; that holds in greater generality, as discussed above.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Čech cohomology is an approximation to sheaf cohomology that is often useful for computations.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Namely, let ${\mathcal {U}}$ be an open cover of a topological space *X*, and let *E* be a sheaf of abelian groups on *X*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Write the open sets in the cover as *U**i* for elements *i* of a set *I*, and fix an ordering of *I*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Thus Čech cohomology is an approximation to sheaf cohomology using only the sections of *E* on finite intersections of the open sets *U**i*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] If every finite intersection *V* of the open sets in ${\mathcal {U}}$ has no higher cohomology with coefficients in *E*, meaning that *H**j*(*V*,*E*) = 0 for all *j* > 0, then the homomorphism from Čech cohomology $H^{j}({\mathcal {U}},E)$ to sheaf cohomology is an isomorphism.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Another approach to relating Čech cohomology to sheaf cohomology is as follows.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] The **Čech cohomology groups** ${\check {H}}^{j}(X,E)$ are defined as the direct limit of $H^{j}({\mathcal {U}},E)$ over all open covers ${\mathcal {U}}$ of *X* (where open covers are ordered by refinement).
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] There is a homomorphism ${\check {H}}^{j}(X,E)\to H^{j}(X,E)$ from Čech cohomology to sheaf cohomology, which is an isomorphism for *j* ≤ 1.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] For arbitrary topological spaces, Čech cohomology can differ from sheaf cohomology in higher degrees.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Conveniently, however, Čech cohomology is isomorphic to sheaf cohomology for any sheaf on a paracompact Hausdorff space.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] The isomorphism ${\check {H}}^{1}(X,E)\cong H^{1}(X,E)$ implies a description of *H*1(*X*,*E*) for any sheaf *E* of abelian groups on a topological space *X*: this group classifies the *E*-**torsors** (also called principal *E*-bundles) over *X*, up to isomorphism.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] For example, on a ringed space (*X*,*O**X*), it follows that the Picard group of invertible sheaves on *X* is isomorphic to the sheaf cohomology group *H*1(*X*,*O**X**), where *O**X** is the sheaf of units in *O**X*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Other names are the cohomology of *X* with **support** in *Y*, or (when *Y* is closed in *X*) **local cohomology**.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] the group of sections of *E* that are supported on *Y*.
