[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Many generalizations are possible using the language of sheaf cohomology.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] For any manifold *X* and field *k*, there is a sheaf *o**X* on *X*, the **orientation sheaf**, which is locally (but perhaps not globally) isomorphic to the constant sheaf *k*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] With coefficients in an arbitrary commutative ring rather than a field, Poincaré duality is naturally formulated as an isomorphism from cohomology to Borel–Moore homology.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] For an *n*-manifold *X*, the dualizing complex *D**X* is isomorphic to the shift *o**X*[*n*] of the orientation sheaf.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] As a result, Verdier duality includes Poincaré duality as a special case.
