[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] In this statement, it is essential to consider sheaf cohomology rather than singular cohomology, unless one makes extra assumptions on *X* such as local contractibility.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Let *f*: *X* → *Y* be a continuous map of topological spaces, and let *E* be a sheaf of abelian groups on *X*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] For example, if *f* is the map from *X* to a point, then *f***E* is the sheaf on a point corresponding to the group *E*(*X*) of global sections of *E*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] The functor *f** from sheaves on *X* to sheaves on *Y* is left exact, but in general not right exact.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] The higher direct image sheaves R*i**f***E* on *Y* are defined as the right derived functors of the functor *f**.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Thus, the higher direct image sheaves describe the cohomology of inverse images of small open sets in *Y*, roughly speaking.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] The **Leray spectral sequence** relates cohomology on *X* to cohomology on *Y*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] The special case where *f* is a fibration and *E* is a constant sheaf plays an important role in homotopy theory under the name of the Serre spectral sequence.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] As a result, any question about sheaf cohomology on a closed subspace can be translated to a question about the direct image sheaf on the ambient space.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] There is a strong finiteness result on sheaf cohomology.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Let *X* be a compact Hausdorff space, and let *R* be a principal ideal domain, for example a field or the ring **Z** of integers.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Then the cohomology groups *H**j*(*X*,*E*) are finitely generated *R*-modules.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] For example, for a compact Hausdorff space *X* that is locally contractible (in the weak sense discussed above), the sheaf cohomology group *H**j*(*X*,**Z**) is finitely generated for every integer *j*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] One case where the finiteness result applies is that of a constructible sheaf.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Let *X* be a topologically stratified space.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] such that each difference *X**i*−*X**i*−1 is a topological manifold of dimension *i*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] A sheaf *E* of *R*-modules on *X* is **constructible** with respect to the given stratification if the restriction of *E* to each stratum *X**i*−*X**i*−1 is locally constant, with stalk a finitely generated *R*-module.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] A sheaf *E* on *X* that is constructible with respect to the given stratification has locally finitely generated cohomology.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] If *X* is compact, it follows that the cohomology groups *H**j*(*X*,*E*) of *X* with coefficients in a constructible sheaf are finitely generated.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] More generally, suppose that *X* is compactifiable, meaning that there is a compact stratified space *W* containing *X* as an open subset, with *W*–*X* a union of connected components of strata.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Then, for any constructible sheaf *E* of *R*-modules on *X*, the *R*-modules *H**j*(*X*,*E*) and *H**c**j*(*X*,*E*) are finitely generated.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] For example, any complex algebraic variety *X*, with its classical (Euclidean) topology, is compactifiable in this sense.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] In algebraic geometry and complex analytic geometry, coherent sheaves are a class of sheaves of particular geometric importance.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] For example, an algebraic vector bundle (on a locally Noetherian scheme) or a holomorphic vector bundle (on a complex analytic space) can be viewed as a coherent sheaf, but coherent sheaves have the advantage over vector bundles that they form an abelian category.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] On a scheme, it is also useful to consider the quasi-coherent sheaves, which include the locally free sheaves of infinite rank.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] A great deal is known about the cohomology groups of a scheme or complex analytic space with coefficients in a coherent sheaf.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] This theory is a key technical tool in algebraic geometry.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] In the 1960s, Grothendieck defined the notion of a **site**, meaning a category equipped with a Grothendieck topology.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] A site *C* axiomatizes the notion of a set of morphisms *V*α → *U* in *C* being a *covering* of *U*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] A topological space *X* determines a site in a natural way: the category *C* has objects the open subsets of *X*, with morphisms being inclusions, and with a set of morphisms *V*α → *U* being called a covering of *U* if and only if *U* is the union of the open subsets *V*α.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] The motivating example of a Grothendieck topology beyond that case was the étale topology on schemes.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Since then, many other Grothendieck topologies have been used in algebraic geometry: the fpqc topology, the Nisnevich topology, and so on.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] The definition of a sheaf works on any site.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] So one can talk about a sheaf of sets on a site, a sheaf of abelian groups on a site, and so on.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] The definition of sheaf cohomology as a derived functor also works on a site.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] So one has sheaf cohomology groups *H**j*(*X*, *E*) for any object *X* of a site and any sheaf *E* of abelian groups.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] For the étale topology, this gives the notion of étale cohomology, which led to the proof of the Weil conjectures.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-cohomology] Crystalline cohomology and many other cohomology theories in algebraic geometry are also defined as sheaf cohomology on an appropriate site.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In mathematics, a **sheaf** (pl.: **sheaves**) is a tool for systematically tracking data (such as sets, abelian groups, rings) attached to the open sets of a topological space and defined locally with regard to them.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For example, for each open set, the data could be the ring of continuous functions defined on that open set.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The field of mathematics that studies sheaves is called **sheaf theory**.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Sheaves are understood conceptually as general and abstract objects.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Their precise definition is rather technical.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] They are specifically defined as **sheaves of sets** or as **sheaves of rings**, for example, depending on the type of data assigned to the open sets.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] There are also maps (or morphisms) from one sheaf to another; sheaves (of a specific type, such as sheaves of abelian groups) with their morphisms on a fixed topological space form a category.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] On the other hand, to each continuous map there is associated both a direct image functor, taking sheaves and their morphisms on the domain to sheaves and morphisms on the codomain, and an inverse image functor operating in the opposite direction.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] These functors, and certain variants of them, are essential parts of sheaf theory.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Due to their general nature and versatility, sheaves have several applications in topology and especially in algebraic and differential geometry.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] First, geometric structures such as that of a differentiable manifold or a scheme can be expressed in terms of a sheaf of rings on the space.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In such contexts, several geometric constructions such as vector bundles or divisors are naturally specified in terms of sheaves.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Second, sheaves provide the framework for a very general cohomology theory, which encompasses also the "usual" topological cohomology theories such as singular cohomology.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Especially in algebraic geometry and the theory of complex manifolds, sheaf cohomology provides a powerful link between topological and geometric properties of spaces.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Sheaves also provide the basis for the theory of *D*-modules, which provide applications to the theory of differential equations.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In addition, generalisations of sheaves to more general settings than topological spaces, such as the notion of a sheaf on a category with respect to some Grothendieck topology, have provided applications to mathematical logic and to number theory.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The ability to restrict data to smaller open subsets gives rise to the concept of presheaves.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Roughly speaking, sheaves are then those presheaves, where local data can be glued to global data.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Informally, the second axiom says it does not matter whether we restrict to W in one step or restrict first to V , then to W .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] A concise functorial reformulation of this definition is given further below.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Many examples of presheaves come from different classes of functions: to any U , one can assign the set $C^{0}(U)$ of continuous real-valued functions on U .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The restriction maps are then just given by restricting a continuous function on U to a smaller open subset $V\subseteq U$ , which again is a continuous function.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The two presheaf axioms are immediately checked, thereby giving an example of a presheaf.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This can be extended to a presheaf of holomorphic functions ${\mathcal {H}}(-)$ and a presheaf of smooth functions $C^{\infty }(-)$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Another common class of examples is assigning to U the set of constant real-valued functions on U .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This presheaf is called the *constant presheaf* associated to $\mathbb {R}$ and is denoted ${\underline {\mathbb {R} }}^{\text{psh}}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Given a presheaf, a natural question to ask is to what extent its sections over an open set U are specified by their restrictions to open subsets of U .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] A *sheaf* is a presheaf whose sections are, in a technical sense, uniquely determined by their restrictions.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] (*Gluing*) Suppose U is an open set, $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$ is an open cover of U with $U_{i}\subseteq U$ for all $i\in I$ , and $\{s_{i}\in {\mathcal {F}}(U_{i})\}_{i\in I}$ is a family of sections.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] If all pairs of sections agree on the overlap of their domains, that is, if $s_{i}|_{U_{i}\cap U_{j}}=s_{j}|_{U_{i}\cap U_{j}}$ for all $i,j\in I$ , then there exists a section $s\in {\mathcal {F}}(U)$ such that $s|_{U_{i}}=s_{i}$ for all $i\in I$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In both of these axioms, the hypothesis on the open cover is equivalent to the assumption that ${\textstyle \bigcup _{i\in I}U_{i}=U}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The section s whose existence is guaranteed by axiom 2 is called the *gluing*, *concatenation*, or *collation* of the sections $s_{i}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Sections $s_{i}$ and $s_{j}$ satisfying the agreement precondition of axiom 2 are often called *compatible* ; thus axioms 1 and 2 together state that *any collection of pairwise compatible sections can be uniquely glued together*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] A *separated presheaf*, or *monopresheaf*, is a presheaf satisfying axiom 1.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The presheaf consisting of continuous functions mentioned above is a sheaf.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This assertion reduces to checking that, given continuous functions $f_{i}:U_{i}\to \mathbb {R}$ which agree on the intersections $U_{i}\cap U_{j}$ , there is a unique continuous function $f:U\to \mathbb {R}$ whose restriction equals the $f_{i}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] By contrast, the constant presheaf is usually *not* a sheaf as it fails to satisfy the locality axiom on the empty set (this is explained in more detail at constant sheaf).
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Presheaves and sheaves are typically denoted by capital letters, F being particularly common, presumably for the French word for sheaf, *faisceau*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Use of calligraphic letters such as ${\mathcal {F}}$ is also common.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] It can be shown that to specify a sheaf, it is enough to specify its restriction to the open sets of a basis for the topology of the underlying space.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Moreover, it can also be shown that it is enough to verify the sheaf axioms above relative to the open sets of a covering.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This observation is used to construct another example which is crucial in algebraic geometry, namely quasi-coherent sheaves.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Here the topological space in question is the spectrum of a commutative ring R , whose points are the prime ideals ${\mathfrak {p}}$ in R .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The open sets $D_{f}:=\{{\mathfrak {p}}\subseteq R,f\notin {\mathfrak {p}}\}$ form a basis for the Zariski topology on this space.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Given an R -module M , there is a sheaf, denoted by ${\tilde {M}}$ on the $\operatorname {Spec} R$ , that satisfies ${\tilde {M}}(D_{f}):=M[1/f],$ where $M[1/f]$ is the localization of M at f .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] There is another characterization of sheaves that is equivalent to the previously discussed.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This characterization is useful in construction of sheaves, for example, if ${\mathcal {F}},{\mathcal {G}}$ are abelian sheaves, then the kernel of sheaves morphism ${\mathcal {F}}\to {\mathcal {G}}$ is a sheaf, since projective limits commute with projective limits.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] On the other hand, the cokernel is not always a sheaf because inductive limits do not necessarily commute with projective limits.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] One way to fix this is to consider Noetherian topological spaces; all open sets are compact so that the cokernel is a sheaf, since finite projective limits commute with inductive limits.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Any such s is commonly called a section of f , and this example is the reason why the elements in ${\mathcal {F}}(U)$ are generally called sections.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This construction is especially important when f is the projection of a fiber bundle onto its base space.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For example, the sheaves of smooth functions are the sheaves of sections of the trivial bundle.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] is the sheaf which assigns to any $U\subseteq \mathbb {C} \setminus \{0\}$ the set of branches of the complex logarithm on U .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Given a point x and an abelian group S , the skyscraper sheaf $S_{x}$ is defined as follows: if U is an open set containing x , then $S_{x}(U)=S$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] If U does not contain x , then $S_{x}(U)=0$ , the trivial group.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The restriction maps are either the identity on S , if both open sets contain x , or the zero map otherwise.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] On an n -dimensional $C^{k}$ -manifold M , there are a number of important sheaves, such as the sheaf of j -times continuously differentiable functions ${\mathcal {O}}_{M}^{j}$ (with $j\leq k$ ).
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Its sections on some open U are the $C^{j}$ -functions $U\to \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For $j=k$ , this sheaf is called the *structure sheaf* and is denoted ${\mathcal {O}}_{M}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The nonzero $C^{k}$ functions also form a sheaf, denoted ${\mathcal {O}}_{X}^{\times }$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Differential forms (of degree p ) also form a sheaf $\Omega _{M}^{p}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In all these examples, the restriction morphisms are given by restricting functions or forms.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The assignment sending U to the compactly supported functions on U is not a sheaf, since there is, in general, no way to preserve this property by passing to a smaller open subset.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Instead, this forms a cosheaf, a dual concept where the restriction maps go in the opposite direction than with sheaves.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] However, taking the dual of these vector spaces does give a sheaf, the sheaf of distributions.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] One of the historical motivations for sheaves have come from studying complex manifolds, complex analytic geometry, and scheme theory from algebraic geometry.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This is because in all of the previous cases, we consider a topological space X together with a structure sheaf ${\mathcal {O}}$ giving it the structure of a complex manifold, complex analytic space, or scheme.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This perspective of equipping a topological space with a sheaf is essential to the theory of locally ringed spaces (see below).
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] One of the main historical motivations for introducing sheaves was constructing a device which keeps track of holomorphic functions on complex manifolds.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This means there exist two compact complex manifolds $X,X'$ which are not isomorphic, but nevertheless their rings of global holomorphic functions, denoted ${\mathcal {H}}(X),{\mathcal {H}}(X')$ , are isomorphic.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Contrast this with smooth manifolds where every manifold M can be embedded inside some $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , hence its ring of smooth functions $C^{\infty }(M)$ comes from restricting the smooth functions from $C^{\infty }(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ , of which there exist plenty.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Another complexity when considering the ring of holomorphic functions on a complex manifold X is given a small enough open set $U\subseteq X$ , the holomorphic functions will be isomorphic to ${\mathcal {H}}(U)\cong {\mathcal {H}}(\mathbb {C} ^{n})$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Sheaves are a direct tool for dealing with this complexity since they make it possible to keep track of the holomorphic structure on the underlying topological space of X on arbitrary open subsets $U\subseteq X$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This means as U becomes more complex topologically, the ring ${\mathcal {H}}(U)$ can be expressed from gluing the ${\mathcal {H}}(U_{i})$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Note that sometimes this sheaf is denoted ${\mathcal {O}}(-)$ or just ${\mathcal {O}}$ , or even ${\mathcal {O}}_{X}$ when we want to emphasize the space the structure sheaf is associated to.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Another common example of sheaves can be constructed by considering a complex submanifold $Y\hookrightarrow X$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] There is an associated sheaf ${\mathcal {O}}_{Y}$ which takes an open subset $U\subseteq X$ and gives the ring of holomorphic functions on $U\cap Y$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This kind of formalism was found to be extremely powerful and motivates a lot of homological algebra such as sheaf cohomology since an intersection theory can be built using these kinds of sheaves from the Serre intersection formula.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Morphisms of sheaves are, roughly speaking, analogous to functions between them.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In contrast to a function between sets, which is simply an assignment of outputs to inputs, morphisms of sheaves are also required to be compatible with the local–global structures of the underlying sheaves.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This idea is made precise in the following definition.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Let ${\mathcal {F}}$ and ${\mathcal {G}}$ be two sheaves of sets (respectively abelian groups, rings, etc.) on X .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] A *morphism* $\varphi :{\mathcal {F}}\to {\mathcal {G}}$ consists of a morphism $\varphi _{U}:{\mathcal {F}}(U)\to {\mathcal {G}}(U)$ of sets (respectively abelian groups, rings, etc.) for each open set U of X , subject to the condition that this morphism is compatible with restrictions.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In other words, for every open subset V of an open set U , the following diagram is commutative.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Indeed, given an ( n -times continuously differentiable) function $f:U\to \mathbb {R}$ (with U in $\mathbb {R}$ open), the restriction (to a smaller open subset V ) of its derivative equals the derivative of $f|_{V}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] With this notion of morphism, sheaves of sets (respectively abelian groups, rings, etc.) on a fixed topological space X form a category.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The general categorical notions of mono-, epi- and isomorphisms can therefore be applied to sheaves.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] These statements give examples of how to work with sheaves using local information, but it's important to note that we cannot check if a morphism of sheaves is an epimorphism in the same manner.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Indeed the statement that maps on the level of open sets $\varphi _{U}\colon {\mathcal {F}}(U)\rightarrow {\mathcal {G}}(U)$ are not always surjective for epimorphisms of sheaves is equivalent to non-exactness of the global sections functor—or equivalently, to non-triviality of sheaf cohomology.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The *stalk* ${\mathcal {F}}_{x}$ of a sheaf ${\mathcal {F}}$ captures the properties of a sheaf "around" a point $x\in X$ , generalizing the germs of functions.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Here, "around" means that, conceptually speaking, one looks at smaller and smaller neighborhoods of the point.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Of course, no single neighborhood will be small enough, which requires considering a limit of some sort.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] the direct limit being over all open subsets of X containing the given point x .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In other words, an element of the stalk is given by a section over some open neighborhood of x , and two such sections are considered equivalent if their restrictions agree on a smaller neighborhood.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The natural morphism ${\mathcal {F}}(U)\to {\mathcal {F}}_{x}$ takes a section s in ${\mathcal {F}}(U)$ to its *germ* $s_{x}$ at x .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This generalises the usual definition of a germ.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In many situations, knowing the stalks of a sheaf is enough to control the sheaf itself.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For example, whether or not a morphism of sheaves is a monomorphism, epimorphism, or isomorphism can be tested on the stalks.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In this sense, a sheaf is determined by its stalks, which are a local data.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] By contrast, the *global* information present in a sheaf, i.e., the *global sections*, i.e., the sections ${\mathcal {F}}(X)$ on the whole space X , typically carry less information.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For example, for a compact complex manifold X , the global sections of the sheaf of holomorphic functions are just $\mathbb {C}$ , since any holomorphic function $X\to \mathbb {C}$ is constant by Liouville's theorem.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] It is frequently useful to take the data contained in a presheaf and to express it as a sheaf.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] It turns out that there is a best possible way to do this.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] It takes a presheaf ${\mathcal {F}}$ and produces a new sheaf $a{\mathcal {F}}$ called the *sheafification* or *sheaf associated to the presheaf* ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For example, the sheafification of the constant presheaf (see above) is called the *constant sheaf*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Despite its name, its sections are *locally* constant functions.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The associated sheaf $a{\mathcal {F}}$ is given by $LL{\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In fact, a is the left adjoint functor to the inclusion functor (or forgetful functor) from the category of sheaves to the category of presheaves, and i is the unit of the adjunction.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In this way, the category of sheaves turns into a Giraud subcategory of presheaves.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This categorical situation is the reason why the sheafification functor appears in constructing cokernels of sheaf morphisms or tensor products of sheaves, but not for kernels, say.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The set $\operatorname {Hom} (F,G)$ of morphisms of sheaves from F to G forms an abelian group (by the abelian group structure of G ).
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] is the sheaf of abelian groups $U\mapsto \operatorname {Hom} (F|_{U},G|_{U})$ where $F|_{U}$ is the sheaf on U given by $(F|_{U})(V)=F(V)$ (note sheafification is not needed here).
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The direct sum of F and G is the sheaf given by $U\mapsto F(U)\oplus G(U)$ , and the tensor product of F and G is the sheaf associated to the presheaf $U\mapsto F(U)\otimes G(U)$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] All of these operations extend to sheaves of modules over a sheaf of rings A ; the above is the special case when A is the constant sheaf ${\underline {\mathbf {Z} }}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Since the data of a (pre-)sheaf depends on the open subsets of the base space, sheaves on different topological spaces are unrelated to each other in the sense that there are no morphisms between them.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] However, given a continuous map $f:X\to Y$ between two topological spaces, pushforward and pullback relate sheaves on X to those on Y and vice versa.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Here V is an open subset of Y , so that its preimage is open in X by the continuity of f .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] where $i:\{x\}\to X$ is the inclusion, and S is regarded as a sheaf on the singleton by $S(\{*\})=S,S(\emptyset )=\emptyset$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For a map between locally compact spaces, the direct image with compact support is a subsheaf of the direct image.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] By definition, $(f_{!}{\mathcal {F}})(V)$ consists of those $s\in {\mathcal {F}}(f^{-1}(V))$ whose support is mapped properly.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] If f is proper itself, then $f_{!}{\mathcal {F}}=f_{*}{\mathcal {F}}$ , but in general they disagree.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The pullback or inverse image goes the other way: it produces a sheaf on X , denoted $f^{-1}{\mathcal {G}}$ out of a sheaf ${\mathcal {G}}$ on Y .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] If f is the inclusion of an open subset, then the inverse image is just a restriction, i.e., it is given by $(f^{-1}{\mathcal {G}})(U)={\mathcal {G}}(U)$ for an open U in X .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] A sheaf ${\mathcal {F}}$ (on some space X ) is called locally constant if $X=\bigcup _{i\in I}U_{i}$ by some open subsets $U_{i}$ such that the restriction of ${\mathcal {F}}$ to all these open subsets is constant.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] On a wide range of topological spaces X , such sheaves are equivalent to representations of the fundamental group $\pi _{1}(X)$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For general maps f , the definition of $f^{-1}{\mathcal {G}}$ is more involved; it is detailed at inverse image functor.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] More generally, if $A\subset X$ is a locally closed subset, then there exists an open U of X containing A such that A is closed in U .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Let $f:A\to U$ and $j:U\to X$ be the natural inclusions.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Then the *extension by zero* of a sheaf ${\mathcal {F}}$ on A is defined by $j_{!}f_{*}F$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Due to its nice behavior on stalks, the extension by zero functor is useful for reducing sheaf-theoretic questions on X to ones on the strata of a stratification, i.e., a decomposition of X into smaller, locally closed subsets.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In addition to (pre-)sheaves as introduced above, where ${\mathcal {F}}(U)$ is merely a set, it is in many cases important to keep track of additional structure on these sections.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For example, the sections of the sheaf of continuous functions naturally form a real vector space, and restriction is a linear map between these vector spaces.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Presheaves with values in an arbitrary category C are defined by first considering the category of open sets on X to be the posetal category $O(X)$ whose objects are the open sets of X and whose morphisms are inclusions.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Then a C -valued presheaf on X is the same as a contravariant functor from $O(X)$ to C .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Morphisms in this category of functors, also known as natural transformations, are the same as the morphisms defined above, as can be seen by unraveling the definitions.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] A particular case of this sheaf condition occurs for U being the empty set, and the index set I also being empty.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In this case, the sheaf condition requires ${\mathcal {F}}(\emptyset )$ to be the terminal object in C .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In several geometrical disciplines, including algebraic geometry and differential geometry, the spaces come along with a natural sheaf of rings, often called the structure sheaf and denoted by ${\mathcal {O}}_{X}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Such a pair $(X,{\mathcal {O}}_{X})$ is called a *ringed space*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Many types of spaces can be defined as certain types of ringed spaces.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Commonly, all the stalks ${\mathcal {O}}_{X,x}$ of the structure sheaf are local rings, in which case the pair is called a *locally ringed space*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For example, an n -dimensional $C^{k}$ manifold M is a locally ringed space whose structure sheaf consists of $C^{k}$ -functions on the open subsets of M .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The property of being a *locally* ringed space translates into the fact that such a function, which is nonzero at a point x , is also non-zero on a sufficiently small open neighborhood of x .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Some authors actually *define* real (or complex) manifolds to be locally ringed spaces that are locally isomorphic to the pair consisting of an open subset of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ (respectively $\mathbb {C} ^{n}$ ) together with the sheaf of $C^{k}$ (respectively holomorphic) functions.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Similarly, schemes, the foundational notion of spaces in algebraic geometry, are locally ringed spaces that are locally isomorphic to the spectrum of a ring.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Most important geometric objects are sheaves of modules.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For example, there is a one-to-one correspondence between vector bundles and locally free sheaves of ${\mathcal {O}}_{X}$ -modules.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This paradigm applies to real vector bundles, complex vector bundles, or vector bundles in algebraic geometry (where ${\mathcal {O}}$ consists of smooth functions, holomorphic functions, or regular functions, respectively).
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Sheaves of solutions to differential equations are D -modules, that is, modules over the sheaf of differential operators.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] On any topological space, modules over the constant sheaf ${\underline {\mathbf {Z} }}$ are the same as sheaves of abelian groups in the sense above.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] There is a different inverse image functor for sheaves of modules over sheaves of rings.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This functor is usually denoted $f^{*}$ and it is distinct from $f^{-1}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Like for modules, coherence is in general a strictly stronger condition than finite presentation.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The Oka coherence theorem states that the sheaf of holomorphic functions on a complex manifold is coherent.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In the examples above it was noted that some sheaves occur naturally as sheaves of sections.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In fact, all sheaves of sets can be represented as sheaves of sections of a topological space called the *étalé space*, from the French word French pronunciation: [étalé], meaning roughly "spread out".
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] If $F\in {\text{Sh}}(X)$ is a sheaf over X , then the **étalé space** (sometimes called the **étale space**) of F is a topological space E together with a local homeomorphism $\pi :E\to X$ such that the sheaf of sections $\Gamma (\pi ,-)$ of $\pi$ is F .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The space E is usually very strange, and even if the sheaf F arises from a natural topological situation, E may not have any clear topological interpretation.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For example, if F is the sheaf of sections of a continuous function $f:Y\to X$ , then $E=Y$ if and only if f is a local homeomorphism.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The étalé space E is constructed from the stalks of F over X .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] As a set, it is their disjoint union and $\pi$ is the obvious map that takes the value x on the stalk of F over $x\in X$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The topology of E is defined as follows.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For each element $s\in F(U)$ and each $x\in U$ , we get a germ of s at x , denoted $[s]_{x}$ or $s_{x}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For any U and $s\in F(U)$ , the union of these points (for all $x\in U$ ) is declared to be open in E .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Notice that each stalk has the discrete topology as subspace topology.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] A morphism between two sheaves determine a continuous map of the corresponding étalé spaces that is compatible with the projection maps (in the sense that every germ is mapped to a germ over the same point).
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This makes the construction into a functor.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The construction above determines an equivalence of categories between the category of sheaves of sets on X and the category of étalé spaces over X .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The construction of an étalé space can also be applied to a presheaf, in which case the sheaf of sections of the étalé space recovers the sheaf associated to the given presheaf.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This construction makes all sheaves into representable functors on certain categories of topological spaces.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] As above, let F be a sheaf on X , let E be its étalé space, and let $\pi :E\to X$ be the natural projection.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Consider the overcategory ${\text{Top}}/X$ of topological spaces over X , that is, the category of topological spaces together with fixed continuous maps to X .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Every object of this category is a continuous map $f:Y\to X$ , and a morphism from $Y\to X$ to $Z\to X$ is a continuous map $Y\to Z$ that commutes with the two maps to X .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] which shows that $\pi :E\to X$ (for the étalé space) represents the functor $\Gamma$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] E is constructed so that the projection map $\pi$ is a covering map.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In algebraic geometry, the natural analog of a covering map is called an étale morphism.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Despite its similarity to "étalé", the word étale [etal] has a different meaning in French.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] It is possible to turn E into a scheme and $\pi$ into a morphism of schemes in such a way that $\pi$ retains the same universal property, but $\pi$ is *not* in general an étale morphism because it is not quasi-finite.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The definition of sheaves by étalé spaces is older than the definition given earlier in the article.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] It is still common in some areas of mathematics such as mathematical analysis.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] As was noted above, this functor does not preserve epimorphisms.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] of open subsets, such that the restriction $g|_{U_{i}}$ are in the image of ${\mathcal {F}}(U_{i})$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] However, g itself need not be in the image of ${\mathcal {F}}(U)$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] ${\mathcal {O}}{\stackrel {\exp }{\to }}{\mathcal {O}}^{\times }$ between the sheaf of holomorphic functions and non-zero holomorphic functions.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This map is an epimorphism, which amounts to saying that any non-zero holomorphic function g (on some open subset in $\mathbb {C}$ , say), admits a complex logarithm *locally*, i.e., after restricting g to appropriate open subsets.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] However, g need not have a logarithm globally.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Sheaf cohomology captures this phenomenon.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] There are several different ways of constructing sheaf cohomology.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Grothendieck (1957) introduced them by defining sheaf cohomology as the derived functor of $\Gamma$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This method is theoretically satisfactory, but, being based on injective resolutions, of little use in concrete computations.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Godement resolutions are another general, but practically inaccessible approach.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Especially in the context of sheaves on manifolds, sheaf cohomology can often be computed using resolutions by soft sheaves, fine sheaves, and flabby sheaves (also known as ***flasque sheaves*** from the French *flasque* meaning flabby).
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For example, a partition of unity argument shows that the sheaf of smooth functions on a manifold is soft.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The higher cohomology groups $H^{i}(U,{\mathcal {F}})$ for $i>0$ vanish for soft sheaves, which gives a way of computing cohomology of other sheaves.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For example, the de Rham complex is a resolution of the constant sheaf ${\underline {\mathbf {R} }}$ on any smooth manifold, so the sheaf cohomology of ${\underline {\mathbf {R} }}$ is equal to its de Rham cohomology.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] A different approach is by Čech cohomology. Čech cohomology was the first cohomology theory developed for sheaves and it is well-suited to concrete calculations, such as computing the coherent sheaf cohomology of complex projective space $\mathbb {P} ^{n}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] It relates sections on open subsets of the space to cohomology classes on the space.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In most cases, Čech cohomology computes the same cohomology groups as the derived functor cohomology.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] However, for some pathological spaces, Čech cohomology will give the correct $H^{1}$ but incorrect higher cohomology groups.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] To get around this, Jean-Louis Verdier developed hypercoverings.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Hypercoverings not only give the correct higher cohomology groups but also allow the open subsets mentioned above to be replaced by certain morphisms from another space.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This flexibility is necessary in some applications, such as the construction of Pierre Deligne's mixed Hodge structures.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Many other coherent sheaf cohomology groups are found using an embedding $i:X\hookrightarrow Y$ of a space X into a space with known cohomology, such as $\mathbb {P} ^{n}$ , or some weighted projective space.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In this way, the known sheaf cohomology groups on these ambient spaces can be related to the sheaves $i_{*}{\mathcal {F}}$ , giving $H^{i}(Y,i_{*}{\mathcal {F}})\cong H^{i}(X,{\mathcal {F}})$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For example, computing the coherent sheaf cohomology of projective plane curves is easily found.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] One big theorem in this space is the Hodge decomposition found using a spectral sequence associated to sheaf cohomology groups, proved by Deligne.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] the sheaf cohomology of a smooth projective variety X , degenerates, meaning $E_{1}=E_{\infty }$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This gives the canonical Hodge structure on the cohomology groups $H^{k}(X,\mathbb {C} )$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] It was later found these cohomology groups can be easily explicitly computed using Griffiths residues.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] These kinds of theorems lead to one of the deepest theorems about the cohomology of algebraic varieties, the decomposition theorem, paving the path for Mixed Hodge modules.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Another clean approach to the computation of some cohomology groups is the Borel–Bott–Weil theorem, which identifies the cohomology groups of some line bundles on flag manifolds with irreducible representations of Lie groups.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This theorem can be used, for example, to easily compute the cohomology groups of all line bundles on projective space and grassmann manifolds.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In many cases there is a duality theory for sheaves that generalizes Poincaré duality.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] See Grothendieck duality and Verdier duality.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This latter functor encompasses the notion of sheaf cohomology since $H^{n}(X,{\mathcal {F}})=R^{n}f_{*}{\mathcal {F}}$ for $f:X\to \{*\}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Like $f_{*}$ , the direct image with compact support $f_{!}$ can also be derived.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] By virtue of the following isomorphism $Rf_{!}{\mathcal {F}}$ parametrizes the cohomology with compact support of the fibers of f : $(R^{i}f_{!}{\mathcal {F}})_{y}=H_{c}^{i}(f^{-1}(y),{\mathcal {F}}).$ This isomorphism is an example of a base change theorem.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In the context of quasi-coherent sheaves on schemes, there is a similar duality known as coherent duality.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Perverse sheaves are certain objects in $D(X)$ , i.e., complexes of sheaves (but not in general sheaves proper).
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] They are an important tool to study the geometry of singularities.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Another important application of derived categories of sheaves is with the derived category of coherent sheaves on a scheme X denoted $D_{Coh}(X)$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] where ${\mathcal {O}}_{Y_{i}}$ are coherent sheaves defined by the ${\mathcal {O}}_{X}$ -modules given by their structure sheaves.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] André Weil's Weil conjectures stated that there was a cohomology theory for algebraic varieties over finite fields that would give an analogue of the Riemann hypothesis.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The cohomology of a complex manifold can be defined as the sheaf cohomology of the locally constant sheaf ${\underline {\mathbf {C} }}$ in the Euclidean topology, which suggests defining a Weil cohomology theory in positive characteristic as the sheaf cohomology of a constant sheaf.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] But the only classical topology on such a variety is the Zariski topology, and the Zariski topology has very few open sets, so few that the cohomology of any Zariski-constant sheaf on an irreducible variety vanishes (except in degree zero).
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Alexandre Grothendieck solved this problem by introducing Grothendieck topologies, which axiomatize the notion of *covering*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Grothendieck's insight was that the definition of a sheaf depends only on the open sets of a topological space, not on the individual points.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Once he had axiomatized the notion of covering, open sets could be replaced by other objects.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] A presheaf takes each one of these objects to data, just as before, and a sheaf is a presheaf that satisfies the gluing axiom with respect to our new notion of covering.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This allowed Grothendieck to define étale cohomology and ℓ-adic cohomology, which eventually were used to prove the Weil conjectures.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] A category with a Grothendieck topology is called a *site*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] A category of sheaves on a site is called a *topos* or a *Grothendieck topos*.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The notion of a topos was later abstracted by William Lawvere and Miles Tierney to define an elementary topos, which has connections to mathematical logic.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p02] The first origins of sheaf theory are hard to pin down; they may be co-extensive with the idea of analytic continuation.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p02] It took about 15 years for a recognisable, free-standing theory of sheaves to emerge from the foundational work on cohomology.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p02] At this point sheaves had become a mainstream part of mathematics, with use by no means restricted to algebraic topology.
[src:sheaf-theory/sheaf-mathematics-p02] It was later discovered that the logic in categories of sheaves is intuitionistic logic (this observation is now often referred to as Kripke–Joyal semantics, but probably should be attributed to a number of authors).
[src:sheaf-theory/sheafification-p01] A *morphism* ${\displaystyle \varphi$ consists of a morphism $\varphi _{U}:{\mathcal {F}}(U)\to {\mathcal {G}}(U)$ of sets (respectively abelian groups, rings, etc.) for each open set U of X , subject to the condition that this morphism is compatible with restrictions.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] In mathematics, the **stalk** of a sheaf is a mathematical construction capturing the behaviour of a sheaf around a given point.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] Sheaves are defined on open sets, but the underlying topological space *X* consists of points.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] It is reasonable to attempt to isolate the behavior of a sheaf at a single fixed point *x* of *X*.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] Conceptually speaking, we do this by looking at small neighborhoods of the point.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] If we look at a sufficiently small neighborhood of *x*, the behavior of the sheaf ${\mathcal {F}}$ on that small neighborhood should be the same as the behavior of ${\mathcal {F}}$ at that point.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] Of course, no single neighborhood will be small enough, so we will have to take a limit of some sort.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] Here the direct limit is indexed over all the open sets containing *x*, with order relation induced by reverse inclusion ( $U\leq V$ , if $U\supseteq V$ ).
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] There is another approach to defining a stalk that is useful in some contexts.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] Choose a point x of X , and let i be the inclusion of the one point space $\{x\}$ into X .
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] Then the stalk ${\mathcal {F}}_{x}$ is the same as the inverse image sheaf $i^{-1}{\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] Notice that the only open sets of the one point space $\{x\}$ are $\{x\}$ and $\emptyset$ , and there is no data over the empty set.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] For some categories **C** the direct limit used to define the stalk may not exist.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] However, it exists for most categories that occur in practice, such as the category of sets or most categories of algebraic objects such as abelian groups or rings, which are namely cocomplete.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] There is a natural morphism ${\mathcal {F}}(U)\to {\mathcal {F}}_{x}$ for any open set U containing *x*: it takes a section s in ${\mathcal {F}}(U)$ to its *germ*, that is, its equivalence class in the direct limit.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] This is a generalization of the usual concept of a germ, which can be recovered by looking at the stalks of the sheaf of continuous functions on *X*.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] The constant sheaf ${\underline {S}}$ associated to some set, S , (or group, ring, etc.) is a sheaf for which ${\underline {S}}_{x}=S$ for all x in X .
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] For example, in the sheaf of analytic functions on an analytic manifold, a germ of a function at a point determines the function in a small neighborhood of a point.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] This is because the germ records the function's power series expansion, and all analytic functions are by definition locally equal to their power series.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] Using analytic continuation, we find that the germ at a point determines the function on any connected open set where the function can be everywhere defined.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] In contrast, for the sheaf of smooth functions on a smooth manifold, germs contain some local information, but are not enough to reconstruct the function on any open neighborhood.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] For example, let $f:\mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R}$ be a bump function that is identically one in a neighborhood of the origin and identically zero far away from the origin.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] On any sufficiently small neighborhood containing the origin, f is identically one, so at the origin it has the same germ as the constant function with value 1.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] Suppose that we want to reconstruct *f* from its germ.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] Even if we know in advance that *f* is a bump function, the germ does not tell us how large its bump is.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] From what the germ tells us, the bump could be infinitely wide, that is, *f* could equal the constant function with value 1.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] We cannot even reconstruct *f* on a small open neighborhood *U* containing the origin, because we cannot tell whether the bump of *f* fits entirely in *U* or whether it is so large that *f* is identically one in *U*.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] On the other hand, germs of smooth functions can distinguish between the constant function with value one and the function $1+e^{-1/x^{2}}$ , because the latter function is not identically one on any neighborhood of the origin.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] This example shows that germs contain more information than the power series expansion of a function, because the power series of $1+e^{-1/x^{2}}$ is identically one.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] (This extra information is related to the fact that the stalk of the sheaf of smooth functions at the origin is a non-Noetherian ring.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] On an affine scheme $X=\mathrm {Spec} (A)$ , the stalk of a quasi-coherent sheaf *${\mathcal {F}}$* corresponding to an A -module M in a point *x* corresponding to a prime ideal p is just the localization $M_{p}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] On any topological space, the skyscraper sheaf associated to a closed point x and a group or ring G has the stalks 0 off x and G on x —hence the name skyscraper.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] This idea makes more sense if one adopts the common visualisation of functions mapping from some space above to a space below; with this visualisation, any function that maps $G\to x$ has G positioned directly above x .
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] The same property holds for any point x if the topological space in question is a T1 space, since every point of a T1 space is closed.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] This feature is the basis of the construction of Godement resolutions, used for example in algebraic geometry to get functorial injective resolutions of sheaves.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] As outlined in the introduction, stalks capture the local behaviour of a sheaf.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] As a sheaf is supposed to be determined by its local restrictions (see gluing axiom), it can be expected that the stalks capture a fair amount of the information that the sheaf is encoding.
[src:sheaf-theory/stalk-sheaf] Both statements are false for presheaves.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] In mathematics, a **topos** (US: /ˈtɒpɒs/, UK: /ˈtoʊpoʊs, ˈtoʊpɒs/; plural **topoi** /ˈtɒpɔɪ/ or /ˈtoʊpɔɪ/, or **toposes**) is a category that behaves like the category of sheaves of sets on a topological space (or more generally, on a site).
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Topoi behave much like the category of sets and possess a notion of localization.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] The **Grothendieck topoi** find applications in algebraic geometry, and more general **elementary topoi** are used in logic.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] The mathematical field that studies topoi is called **topos theory**.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Since the introduction of sheaves into mathematics in the 1940s, a major theme has been to study a space by studying sheaves on a space.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] This idea was expounded by Alexander Grothendieck by introducing the notion of a "topos".
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] The main utility of this notion is in the abundance of situations in mathematics where topological heuristics are very effective, but an honest topological space is lacking; it is sometimes possible to find a topos formalizing the heuristic.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] An important example of this programmatic idea is the étale topos of a scheme.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Another illustration of the capability of Grothendieck topoi to incarnate the “essence” of different mathematical situations is given by their use as "bridges" for connecting theories which, albeit written in possibly very different languages, share a common mathematical content.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] A Grothendieck topos is a category C which satisfies any one of the following three properties.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Here $\operatorname {Presh} (D)$ denotes the category of contravariant functors from D to the category of sets; such a contravariant functor is frequently called a presheaf.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] The last axiom needs the most explanation.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] If *X* is an object of *C*, an "equivalence relation" *R* on *X* is a map *R* → *X* × *X* in *C* such that for any object *Y* in *C*, the induced map Hom(*Y*, *R*) → Hom(*Y*, *X*) × Hom(*Y*, *X*) gives an ordinary equivalence relation on the set Hom(*Y*, *X*).
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Since *C* has colimits we may form the coequalizer of the two maps *R* → *X*; call this *X*/*R*.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Giraud's theorem already gives "sheaves on sites" as a complete list of examples.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Note, however, that nonequivalent sites often give rise to equivalent topoi.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] As indicated in the introduction, sheaves on ordinary topological spaces motivate many of the basic definitions and results of topos theory.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] The category of sets is an important special case: it plays the role of a point in topos theory.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Indeed, a set may be thought of as a sheaf on a point since functors on the singleton category with a single object and only the identity morphism are just specific sets in the category of sets.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Similarly, there is a topos $BG$ for any group G which is equivalent to the category of G -sets.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] We construct this as the category of presheaves on the category with one object, but now the set of morphisms is given by the group G .
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Since any functor must give a G -action on the target, this gives the category of G -sets.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Similarly, for a groupoid ${\mathcal {G}}$ the category of presheaves on ${\mathcal {G}}$ gives a collection of sets indexed by the set of objects in ${\mathcal {G}}$ , and the automorphisms of an object in ${\mathcal {G}}$ has an action on the target of the functor.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] More exotic examples, and the *raison d'être* of topos theory, come from algebraic geometry.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] The basic example of a topos comes from the Zariski topos of a scheme.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] For each scheme X there is a site ${\text{Open}}(X)$ (of objects given by open subsets and morphisms given by inclusions) whose category of presheaves forms the Zariski topos $(X)_{Zar}$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] But once distinguished classes of morphisms are considered, there are multiple generalizations of this which leads to non-trivial mathematics.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Moreover, topoi give the foundations for studying schemes purely as functors on the category of algebras.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] To a scheme and even a stack one may associate an étale topos, an fppf topos, or a Nisnevich topos.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Another important example of a topos is from the crystalline site.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] In the case of the étale topos, these form the foundational objects of study in anabelian geometry, which studies objects in algebraic geometry that are determined entirely by the structure of their étale fundamental group.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Topos theory is, in some sense, a generalization of classical point-set topology.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] One should therefore expect to see old and new instances of pathological behavior.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] For instance, there is an example due to Pierre Deligne of a nontrivial topos that has no points (see below for the definition of points of a topos).
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] If X and Y are topoi, a *geometric morphism* $u:X\to Y$ is a pair of adjoint functors (*u*∗,*u*∗) (where *u*∗ : *Y* → *X* is left adjoint to *u*∗ : *X* → *Y*) such that *u*∗ preserves finite limits.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Note that *u*∗ automatically preserves colimits by virtue of having a right adjoint.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] By Freyd's adjoint functor theorem, to give a geometric morphism *X* → *Y* is to give a functor *u*∗: *Y* → *X* that preserves finite limits and all small colimits.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Thus geometric morphisms between topoi may be seen as analogues of maps of locales.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] If X and Y are topological spaces and u is a continuous map between them, then the pullback and pushforward operations on sheaves yield a geometric morphism between the associated topoi for the sites ${\text{Open}}(X),{\text{Open}}(Y)$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] A point of a topos X is defined as a geometric morphism from the topos of sets to X .
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] If *X* is an ordinary space and *x* is a point of *X*, then the functor that takes a sheaf *F* to its stalk *Fx* has a right adjoint (the "skyscraper sheaf" functor), so an ordinary point of *X* also determines a topos-theoretic point.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] These may be constructed as the pullback-pushforward along the continuous map *x*: *1* → *X*.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] For the etale topos $(X)_{et}$ of a space X , a point is a bit more refined of an object.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Given a point $x:{\text{Spec}}(\kappa (x))\to X$ of the underlying scheme X a point $x'$ of the topos $(X)_{et}$ is then given by a separable field extension k of $\kappa (x)$ such that the associated map $x':{\text{Spec}}(k)\to X$ factors through the original point x .
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Then, the factorization map ${\text{Spec}}(k)\to {\text{Spec}}(\kappa (x))$ is an etale morphism of schemes.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] More precisely, those are the *global* points.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] They are not adequate in themselves for displaying the space-like aspect of a topos, because a non-trivial topos may fail to have any.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] *Generalized* points are geometric morphisms from a topos *Y* (the *stage of definition*) to *X*.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] There are enough of these to display the space-like aspect.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] For example, if *X* is the classifying topos *S*[*T*] for a geometric theory *T*, then the universal property says that its points are the models of *T* (in any stage of definition *Y*).
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] A geometric morphism (*u*∗,*u*∗) is *essential* if *u*∗ has a further left adjoint *u*!, or equivalently (by the adjoint functor theorem) if *u*∗ preserves not only finite but all small limits.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] A **ringed topos** is a pair (*X*,*R*), where *X* is a topos and *R* is a commutative ring object in *X*.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Most of the constructions of ringed spaces go through for ringed topoi.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] The category of *R*-module objects in *X* is an abelian category with enough injectives.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] A more useful abelian category is the subcategory of quasi-coherent *R*-modules: these are *R*-modules that admit a presentation.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Another important class of ringed topoi, besides ringed spaces, are the étale topoi of Deligne–Mumford stacks.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Michael Artin and Barry Mazur associated to the site underlying a topos a pro-simplicial set (up to homotopy).
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] (It's better to consider it in Ho(pro-SS); see Edwards) Using this inverse system of simplicial sets one may *sometimes* associate to a homotopy invariant in classical topology an inverse system of invariants in topos theory.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] The study of the pro-simplicial set associated to the étale topos of a scheme is called étale homotopy theory.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] In good cases (if the scheme is Noetherian and geometrically unibranch), this pro-simplicial set is pro-finite.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Since the early 20th century, the predominant axiomatic foundation of mathematics has been set theory, in which all mathematical objects are ultimately represented by sets (including functions, which map between sets).
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] More recent work in category theory allows this foundation to be generalized using topoi; each topos completely defines its own mathematical framework.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] The category of sets forms a familiar topos, and working within this topos is equivalent to using traditional set-theoretic mathematics.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] But one could instead choose to work with many alternative topoi.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] A standard formulation of the axiom of choice makes sense in any topos, and there are topoi in which it is invalid.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Constructivists will be interested to work in a topos without the law of excluded middle.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] If symmetry under a particular group *G* is of importance, one can use the topos consisting of all *G*-sets.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] It is also possible to encode an algebraic theory, such as the theory of groups, as a topos, in the form of a classifying topos.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] The individual models of the theory, i.e. the groups in our example, then correspond to functors from the encoding topos to the category of sets that respect the topos structure.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] When used for foundational work a topos will be defined axiomatically; set theory is then treated as a special case of topos theory.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Building from category theory, there are multiple equivalent definitions of a topos.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Formally, a **power object** of an object X is a pair $(PX,\ni _{X})$ with ${\ni _{X}}\subseteq PX\times X$ , which classifies relations, in the following sense.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] First note that for every object I , a morphism $r\colon I\to PX$ ("a family of subsets") induces a subobject $\{(i,x)~|~x\in r(i)\}\subseteq I\times X$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Formally, this is defined by pulling back $\ni _{X}$ along $r\times X:I\times X\to PX\times X$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] The universal property of a power object is that every relation arises in this way, giving a bijective correspondence between relations $R\subseteq I\times X$ and morphisms $r\colon I\to PX$ .
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] In some applications, the role of the subobject classifier is pivotal, whereas power objects are not.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Thus some definitions reverse the roles of what is defined and what is derived.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] A *logical functor* is a functor between topoi that preserves finite limits and power objects.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Logical functors preserve the structures that topoi have.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] In particular, they preserve finite colimits, subobject classifiers, and exponential objects.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] A topos as defined above can be understood as a Cartesian closed category for which the notion of subobject of an object has an elementary or first-order definition.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] This notion, as a natural categorical abstraction of the notions of subset of a set, subgroup of a group, and more generally subalgebra of any algebraic structure, predates the notion of topos.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] It is definable in any category, not just topoi, in second-order language, i.e. in terms of classes of morphisms instead of individual morphisms, as follows.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Given two monics *m*, *n* from respectively *Y* and *Z* to *X*, we say that *m* ≤ *n* when there exists a morphism *p*: *Y* → *Z* for which *np* = *m*, inducing a preorder on monics to *X*.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] When *m* ≤ *n* and *n* ≤ *m* we say that *m* and *n* are equivalent.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] The subobjects of *X* are the resulting equivalence classes of the monics to it.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] In a topos "subobject" becomes, at least implicitly, a first-order notion, as follows.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] As noted above, a topos is a category *C* having all finite limits and hence in particular the empty limit or final object 1.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] It is then natural to treat morphisms of the form *x*: 1 → *X* as *elements* *x* ∈ *X*.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Morphisms *f*: *X* → *Y* thus correspond to functions mapping each element *x* ∈ *X* to the element *fx* ∈ *Y*, with application realized by composition.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] One might then think to define a subobject of *X* as an equivalence class of monics *m*: *X′* → *X* having the same image { *mx* | *x* ∈ *X′* }.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] The catch is that two or more morphisms may correspond to the same function, that is, we cannot assume that *C* is concrete in the sense that the functor *C*(1,-): *C* → **Set** is faithful.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Whereas the second-order definition makes *G* and the subgraph of all self-loops of *G* (with their vertices) distinct subobjects of *G* (unless every edge is, and every vertex has, a self-loop), this image-based one does not.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] This can be addressed for the graph example and related examples via the Yoneda Lemma as described in the Further examples section below, but this then ceases to be first-order.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Topoi provide a more abstract, general, and first-order solution.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] As noted above, a topos *C* has a subobject classifier Ω, namely an object of *C* with an element *t* ∈ Ω, the *generic subobject* of *C*, having the property that every monic *m*: *X′* → *X* arises as a pullback of the generic subobject along a unique morphism *f*: *X* → Ω, as per Figure 1.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Now the pullback of a monic is a monic, and all elements including *t* are monics since there is only one morphism to 1 from any given object, whence the pullback of *t* along *f*: *X* → Ω is a monic.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] The monics to *X* are therefore in bijection with the pullbacks of *t* along morphisms from *X* to Ω.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] The latter morphisms partition the monics into equivalence classes each determined by a morphism *f*: *X* → Ω, the characteristic morphism of that class, which we take to be the subobject of *X* characterized or named by *f*.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] All this applies to any topos, whether or not concrete.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] In the concrete case, namely *C*(1,-) faithful, for example the category of sets, the situation reduces to the familiar behavior of functions.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Here the monics *m*: *X′* → *X* are exactly the injections (one-one functions) from *X′* to *X*, and those with a given image { *mx* | *x* ∈ *X′* } constitute the subobject of *X* corresponding to the morphism *f*: *X* → Ω for which *f*−1(*t*) is that image.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] The monics of a subobject will in general have many domains, all of which however will be in bijection with each other.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] To summarize, this first-order notion of subobject classifier implicitly defines for a topos the same equivalence relation on monics to *X* as had previously been defined explicitly by the second-order notion of subobject for any category.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Every Grothendieck topos is an elementary topos, but the converse is not true (since every Grothendieck topos is cocomplete, which is not required from an elementary topos).
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] The categories of finite sets, of finite *G*-sets (actions of a group *G* on a finite set), and of finite graphs are elementary topoi that are not Grothendieck topoi.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] If *C* is a small category, then the functor category **Set***C* (consisting of all covariant functors from *C* to sets, with natural transformations as morphisms) is a topos.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] For instance, the category **Grph** of graphs of the kind permitting multiple directed edges between two vertices is a topos.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] Such a graph consists of two sets, an edge set and a vertex set, and two functions *s,t* between those sets, assigning to every edge *e* its source *s*(*e*) and target *t*(*e*).
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] **Grph** is thus equivalent to the functor category **Set***C*, where *C* is the category with two objects *E* and *V* and two morphisms *s,t*: *E* → *V* giving respectively the source and target of each edge.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] The Yoneda lemma asserts that *C*op embeds in **Set***C* as a full subcategory.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] The natural transformations from *V'* to an arbitrary graph (functor) *G* constitute the vertices of *G* while those from *E'* to *G* constitute its edges.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] That is, a morphism of graphs can be understood as a *pair* of functions, one mapping the vertices and the other the edges, with application still realized as composition but now with multiple sorts of *generalized* elements.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] This shows that the traditional concept of a concrete category as one whose objects have an underlying set can be generalized to cater for a wider range of topoi by allowing an object to have multiple underlying sets, that is, to be multisorted.
[src:sheaf-theory/topos] The category of abelian groups is also not a topos, for a similar reason: every group homomorphism must map 0 to 0.
